**caution!!!: at 18:08 - 19:43 min. a very loud peck**  -- " **..& -Tret calls** "  --  in a kind of old water area in bobingen - sound was trapped - for 11 hours... recorded with zoomh1n.

.. it is now very actually moult... you hear e.g. speciale mainly Phylloscopus collybita strong.

- this area i had others sessions-birdering in spring... [see here all recordings from this backwater area](https://xeno-canto.org/explore?query=rec:%20uhl%20rmk:%20Kusa_sierS_müh%20loc:%20bobingen%20year:%202022) .

place: (Kusa_sierS_träp_ruf_moult03 ).

**here:** .  -- this id-bird .. is to hear some times **'longer-series-of Tret calls', e.g. between** 11:15 - 11:54 min.  ... ?  ..(IMO discribed as ...here) ... at about 16:25 min. a single **call** in more forground  .followed at 17:50 min. till end are calls in background .  ..

.. in the first part are to hear: e.g. Dendroc. major ...and faint in background young birds of this species ... a 2nd woodpecker at about 05:00 and 15:34 min. P. viridis .. and also more in background C. chloris..  S. europaea  ...- at 6:55 min. flight syllable of Alcedo atthis, at 08:11 min. a louder barking of a nice dog .. a Columba palumbus at 10:26 and 12:25 min.  ..

..and perhaps  C.B. is also a young bird to hear ?

Great Britain (near  Oxford), Oxfordshire, England
recordings.rmk:
Phone recording. Same bird as in XC631068 and XC631071; same location as XC630988 one day later and very likely same bird given same unusual song featuring rising "weep" notes. Seen but not clearly enough to give any useful visual indicators, bird always mobile. At one point what appeared to be the same bird sang a typical P. c. collybita phrase without "weep" notes, unfortunately not recorded.

Song phrases at 0:02 - 0:05 and 0:18 - 0:21.

Forum discussion here: https://www.xeno-canto.org/forum/topic/42420

recordings.loc: Great Britain (near  Oxford), Oxfordshire, England
recordings.rmk:
Phone recording of a presumed Phylloscopus collybita song, but doesn't appear to match any subspecies' typical song. Mainly alternated 1:1 between typical P. c. collybita "tyew!" and pure upslurred "weep" notes more reminiscent of components of P. c. tristis or P. ibericus song but unlike either of those in structure. Unfortunately I only managed to record one short phrase (0:06 - 0:08) before it stopped singing, but each previous phrase it had similarly slid up and down (like a coal tit!), occasionally repeating one unit twice as in P. c. collybita's typical song. Does anyone recognise this song type or have any thoughts as to the origins or genetic identity of the bird? Are P. c. collybita known to ever incorporate "weep" notes into the song like this?

One apparent P. c. collybita-like "huit" call at 0:29; I didn't notice it at the time and don't know if it was from the same bird.

I only saw the bird in silhouette at a distance so can't comment on visual characteristics.
